To determine whether an intervention (e.g., anti-poaching patrols) is truly effective, the document outlines a core formula and three key factors:​

1. The "True Impact" Formula You cannot simply look at the results after an intervention to claim success. True impact is calculated as follows:​

[Change in the intervention area] - [Change in the control area] = [True Impact]​

​

2. Three Factors You Need to Identify​

The Baseline: Where do you start? You need specific figures before starting the intervention to use as a benchmark for comparison.​

Example: Before patrols, there was an average of 10 traps per kilometer.​

The Before & After: What has changed? However, looking only at "before and after" is not enough, as there may be external factors at play.​

Example: After one month of patrolling, the number of traps decreased to 2/km. Is this due to your patrolling, or because the rainy season reduced the number of poachers?​

The Control Group: What would happen if you did nothing? This refers to a similar area but without intervention, used for comparison.​

​

3. Practical Illustrative ExampleScenario: Protecting turtles in two rivers Assume you implement protection measures for turtle nests in River A (the intervention area) and monitor River B (the control group, where nothing is done). Both rivers have similar conditions.​

In River A (with intervention): The rate of turtle nest destruction decreased from 70% to 46% (a 24% reduction).​

In River B (without intervention): This rate also decreased naturally from 62% to 56.6% (a 5.4% natural reduction).​

Conclusion: The actual impact of your intervention is only 18.6% (24% minus 5.4% natural decline). Without the control group in River B, you might have mistakenly claimed a 24% success rate.​

​

4. Why is it so complicated? The literature indicates that situations often change over time due to:​

Seasonal rhythms: Crime may naturally decrease at certain times of the year.​

Pre-existing trends: The problem may already be on a downward trend before you begin.​

External factors: There might be another police crackdown or a sudden drop in market demand.​

​

​

In short: To prove an intervention is effective, you must demonstrate that the change in the intervention area is significantly better than the natural change in the area without intervention."​

​Choosing whether to measure change using the Average or the Trend will determine how you evaluate the success of an intervention.​

1. Measuring by Average This method focuses on the question: "Is the overall level of the problem lower than before?"​

Evaluation: Compare the average value of the data before and after the intervention.​

Example: In the first six months of the year, there was an average of 10 poaching incidents per month. After warning signs were installed, the average dropped to 3 incidents per month in the following six months.​

Conclusion: If you only look at the average, the decrease from 10 to 3 suggests that the intervention was effective.​

2. Measuring by Trend This method focuses on the question: "Has the direction of the problem changed?" (e.g., from increasing to decreasing).​

Evaluation: Analyze the data curve over time to identify changes in slope or direction.​

Example: If the number of violations was steadily increasing (upward trend) but began to steadily decrease (downward trend) after the patrol team was deployed.​

Conclusion: Successfully reversing a trend provides strong evidence that the intervention had a direct impact.​

Why is looking at just the "Average" insufficient? Relying solely on the average can be misleading in several scenarios:​

Accelerated Decline: If the data shows the problem was already decreasing before you started, a lower average is inevitable. Your true impact is only proven if you make the rate of decline steeper than the pre-existing trend.​

Regression to the Mean: If you intervene when the problem is at an all-time high (e.g., a sudden outbreak), the problem may naturally return to its normal level. You might mistakenly claim credit for a decline that would have happened regardless.​

Static Trend: In some cases, the number of incidents drops immediately after intervention but then stabilizes. While the average decreases, the long-term trend remains unchanged, suggesting the intervention did not fully solve the root cause.​

Advice: To gain the most accurate insight, you should graph the data over time rather than relying on isolated figures. This reveals the "big picture" and shows whether you have truly changed the nature of the problem."​

​This helps you avoid making sweeping generalizations when observing data changes. There are three natural phenomena that can mislead you regarding your actual effectiveness:​

1. Accelerated Decline This occurs when the problem was already trending downwards before you began your intervention.​

Explanation: If you only compare the average before and after, you will notice a decrease. In reality, however, this decline is driven by the pre-existing trend. Your real impact lies only in making the curve steeper—meaning the problem decreases even faster than before.​

Example: The number of poaching incidents is decreasing by 5% annually as people switch to other professions. After your campaign, it decreases by 20% per year. Your true impact is the additional 15%, not the entire 20%.​

2. Regression to the Mean This happens when a problem naturally subsides from an unusually high level.​

Explanation: You may start a project exactly when a problem is at its "peak" (e.g., a poaching outbreak due to a specific event). Subsequently, the situation will naturally stabilize and return to normal regardless of your actions.​

Example: Following the COVID-19 pandemic, poaching surged due to job losses. As the economy stabilized, incidents automatically decreased. If you launch a project during such a peak, the downward trend on the graph might simply reflect a natural social "cooling-down" period.​

3. Seasonal Rhythms These are cyclical increases and decreases over time (e.g., months, seasons, or festivals).​

Explanation: Many violations are time-sensitive. If you overlook this, you may be misled by these periodic fluctuations. It is advisable to compare equivalent timeframes (e.g., July of this year versus July of last year) to avoid discrepancies.​

Example: During the dry season, hunters can easily access the forest, leading to a spike in violations; during the rainy season, flooding causes a significant decrease. If you begin patrolling at the end of the dry season, a drop in violations during the rainy season may be due to the weather rather than your efforts.​

In short: To determine if you are truly making an impact, you must compare the "counterfactual" (what would have happened if you were not there) against the actual observed data. The gap between these two lines is what truly represents your achievement.​

​Anticipating Complex System Responses involves understanding the 'non-linear' ways in which crime or the environment reacts to an intervention. Rather than expecting an immediate reduction, the document outlines three common scenarios for which you should be prepared:​

1. Preventing a Further Rise​

Sometimes, success is not defined by reducing the figures, but by preventing them from increasing further.​

Explanation: Without your intervention, the problem would continue to escalate (an upward curve). By intervening, you flatten this curve, effectively halting the growth of the problem.​

Example: Hunting incidents are increasing by 10% monthly due to market demand. You deploy guard posts; while the number of incidents does not decrease, it stabilizes at the current level instead of continuing its predicted climb.​

2. Time Lag​

A system's response does not always occur immediately after action is taken.​

Explanation: It takes time for information regarding the intervention to diffuse or for a shift in perception to translate into a change in behavior. This is particularly common when outreach activities are conducted far from the actual site.​

Example: You launch a campaign in the city to change perceptions about consuming bushmeat. It may take 3 to 6 months for this information to reach restaurants and consumers before trapping incidents in the field begin to decline.​

3. Premature Decline / Anticipatory Benefits​

This is an intriguing phenomenon where the problem decreases before the intervention is officially launched.​

Explanation: This occurs when offenders believe that an intervention has begun or is imminent, leading them to cease their activities out of fear. Research indicates this happens in approximately 40% of crime prevention studies.​

Example: You announce that "Next month, a smart surveillance camera system will be installed throughout the entire reserve." Even though no cameras are in place yet, poachers may stop their activities this week for fear of being recorded.​

In summary: When assessing impact, you should not always expect a sudden, sharp drop in the graph immediately following an intervention. Understanding these complex reactions allows you to accurately value the project, even if results are delayed or manifest simply as the stabilization of a deteriorating situation​

​Simply comparing Before & After data is insufficient to determine whether an intervention is truly effective, as the world is constantly changing due to factors beyond your control.​

​

1. The Flaw in the "Before & After" Method​

When poaching decreases following increased patrols, it is often assumed that your efforts are the cause. However, this method relies on the false assumption that if you do nothing, everything will remain static. In reality, there are numerous "alternative pathways" leading to such a decrease that may be entirely unrelated to your actions.​

​

2. Three "Confounding Factors"​

The document identifies three reasons why a "decrease" might be misleading:​

Natural Decline in Demand (Pathway 1): For instance, a bushmeat consumption festival has just concluded, leading to a natural drop in demand.​

External Intervention (Pathway 2): A separate police unit may have apprehended a poaching ringleader in a case unrelated to your project.​

Shift in Tactics (Pathway 3): Poachers may not have stopped; they might have simply altered their methods or relocated, making it harder for your patrol team to detect their activities.​

​

3. Practical Example​

Imagine you are protecting turtle nests at River A and observe the theft rate drop from 70% to 46% (a 24% reduction). You might hastily conclude that the project is a resounding success.​

However, when examining River B (the control group, where no action was taken), the theft rate also decreased from 62% to 56.6% (a 5.4% natural reduction).​

Analysis: The decrease in River B suggests that a common factor (such as weather or market shifts) is contributing to the reduction in turtle nest poaching across the region.​

The Reality: Your actual impact is only 18.6% (the 24% reduction minus the 5.4% natural decline), not the 24% initially assumed.​

​

4. Additional Confounding Factors​

Furthermore, "Before & After" data can be skewed by:​

Pre-existing Trends: The problem was already declining before the intervention began.​

Regression to the Mean: You initiated the project when violations were at a record high; subsequently, they naturally returned to average levels regardless of your intervention.​

Seasonal Rhythms: Violations may have decreased simply because the rainy season began, hindering poachers' access to the forest.​

​

Advice: To eliminate these confounding factors, you must establish a Control Area—a location with similar conditions but no intervention—to serve as a baseline for comparison​

​To accurately assess the true impact of a project, you must establish a Control Situation. Đây là nơi câu hỏi "Điều gì sẽ xảy ra nếu bạn không làm gì?" được giải đáp.​

A control situation is considered valid only when it satisfies the following two key criteria:​

1. Comparability​

The control situation must share similar "circumstances" with the intervention area to ensure that external factors affect both equally.​

Consistent Problem: Both locations must experience the same type of violation and be measured using identical, precise methods.​

Same Seasonal Rhythms: Both must be subject to the same natural cycles (e.g., rainy seasons, breeding seasons).​

Similar Socio-Economic Factors: Both areas should be influenced by comparable external drivers, such as market demand or local economic conditions.​

2. Independence (Isolation from Intervention)​

The control area must remain separate to avoid being "contaminated" by your activities.​

Sufficient Distance: The control area must be far enough from the intervention site so that your activities do not inadvertently spill over.​

Avoiding "Crime Displacement": You must ensure that offenders do not simply relocate to the control area to commit crimes due to your patrols in the intervention area. If this occurs, it will artificially worsen the control data, making your results appear more successful than they truly are.​

​
